{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01VbK3EgWJuZ7rD5uBTuVB5G","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `read` role is NOT in the list of built-in roles! This is interesting. Elasticsearch 8.11.1 doesn't have a built-in `read` role? Let me check the documentation...\n\nActually looking at this more carefully, Elasticsearch 8.x removed some roles that existed in older versions. Let me think about what role provides read access to indices in ES 8.x...\n\nWait, actually looking at the list of roles provided by the precondition warning:\n```\nKnown roles: [kibana_dashboard_only_user, apm_system, watcher_admin, viewer, logstash_system, rollup_user, kibana_user, beats_admin, remote_monitoring_agent, rollup_admin, data_frame_transforms_admin, snapshot_user, monitoring_user, enrich_user, kibana_admin, logstash_admin, editor, machine_learning_user, data_frame_transforms_user, machine_learning_admin, watcher_user, a\n```\n\nIndeed, `read` is NOT in the list of known roles. Elasticsearch 7.x used to have a `read` role, but it seems ES 8.x doesn't have it as a built-in role anymore.\n\nI'm realizing I've been conflating index privileges with role names. `read` is an index privilege that allows reading documents, but it's not a valid role name to assign to users. The `users_roles` file is trying to assign a role called `read` to `report-user`, but since there's no built-in role with that name in Elasticsearch 8.x, it can't be resolved. The user needs to be assigned an actual role like `viewer` or a custom role that grants read access instead. I'm realizing the `viewer` role is Kibana-specific and won't help here. For index-level read access, I need to create a custom `read` role through the Elasticsearch Security API that grants read privileges on indices, which would make the role assignment in users_roles actually work.\n\nNow I'm checking whether to define this role in the `roles.yml` file or create it via the API. The StatefulSet has the aggregate secret mounted, so I should verify if `roles.yml` is actually being used by the volumeMount configuration.\n\nLooking at the volumeMount setup, I only mounted the `users` and `users_roles` files, not `roles.yml`. Since there's no override for roles in the config directory, the simplest approach is to create the `read` role directly through the Elasticsearch API using the native realm, which avoids needing to restart any pods.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1002,"cache_read_input_tokens":70983,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1002},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c656a6e4-a5db-4687-8cb3-0e9353c86e23","uuid":"74db94ff-feb0-428b-ad7b-fe9185db8d22","request_id":"req_011Cc9Z2kTf88xyaEbM5xUZw"}
