{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012hKiNedWV7Asutoq1VpGq3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All checks pass. Here's a summary of what was done:\n\n**Root cause:** The file realm secrets (`es-file-realm-aggregate` with ops-user, `user-provided-file-realm` with report-user) existed but were never mounted on the Elasticsearch pods — the StatefulSet used an emptyDir volume + init container that only wrote the `elastic` user.\n\n**Fix applied in three steps:**\n\n1. **Merged secrets** — concatenated report-user's `users` and `users_roles` entries into `es-file-realm-aggregate`, so the aggregate now contains both ops-user and report-user with their bcrypt hashes.\n\n2. **Patched the StatefulSet** — changed the `es-users` volume from an emptyDir (with a broken init container that wrote invalid entries) to a secret volume backed by `es-file-realm-aggregate`. This triggered a rolling restart that reloaded the file realm with both users.\n\n3. **Created the `read` role** — Elasticsearch 8.x has no built-in role named `read` (it's only an index privilege name). Created it via the security API granting `read` + `view_index_metadata` on all indices. Also seeded the `app-data` index since it hadn't been created.\n\n**Result:** All 3 nodes running (green cluster), `ops-user` authenticates as superuser, `report-user` authenticates and reads the `app-data` index — existing `elastic` user unaffected."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":885,"cache_read_input_tokens":74619,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":885},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c656a6e4-a5db-4687-8cb3-0e9353c86e23","uuid":"3c82181f-900f-4a14-846c-d0eb0fcd9a88","request_id":"req_011Cc9Z9NXVb8zNxfFPY